Data Cleaning

In[3]:
# Removing duplicate rows
df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

# Removing double/multiple spaces in column names and make them consistent
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip().str.lower().str.replace(r'\s+', '_', regex=True)

# Standardizing column names
df.columns = [col.strip().lower().replace(" ", "_") for col in df.columns]

# Removing extra spaces inside string-type values
object_cols = df.select_dtypes(include='object').columns
for col in object_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].str.strip().str.replace(r'\s+', ' ', regex=True)

# Check for missing values
print("\nMissing values:")
print(df.isnull().sum())

In[4]:
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer

# Dropping rows with missing life_expectancy (target variable)
df = df.dropna(subset=["life_expectancy"])
 
# Separating numeric and non-numeric data
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include='number')
non_numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(exclude='number').reset_index(drop=True)

# Applying IterativeImputer (Replacing missing values using relationships across other columns)
imp = IterativeImputer(random_state=0)
numeric_imputed = pd.DataFrame(imp.fit_transform(numeric_df), columns=numeric_df.columns)

# Merge back
df_imputed = pd.concat([non_numeric_df, numeric_imputed], axis=1)

# Checking for missing values in df_imputed
df_imputed.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Histogram + KDE
sns.histplot(df_imputed['life_expectancy'], kde=True, bins=30)
plt.title("Distribution of Life Expectancy")
plt.xlabel("Life Expectancy")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

# Boxplot
sns.boxplot(x=df_imputed['life_expectancy'])
plt.title("Boxplot of Life Expectancy")
plt.show()

1. Histogram + KDE Plot (Distribution of Life Expectancy)

  • Shape: The distribution is right-skewed (longer tail on the left).
  • Peak: Most values cluster between 65 and 80 years.
  • Tail: A smaller number of countries have lower life expectancy (below 60), causing the skew.
  • KDE: Gives a smoothed estimate of the distribution. The main mode (peak) is around 7275 years.

Interpretation:

  • Life expectancy is not perfectly normally distributed; it has a moderate skew.
  • A majority of observations fall within a healthy range, but there's a significant portion of lower values (likely countries with poor healthcare or high mortality).

2. Boxplot (Life Expectancy)

  • Median: The thick line inside the box shows the median life expectancy, around 73 years.
  • IQR (box): Middle 50% of countries fall between ~65 and ~78 years.
  • Whiskers: Extend to the minimum and maximum non-outlier values.
  • Outliers: Points on the left (around 3850) are outliers, countries with significantly lower life expectancy.

Interpretation:

  • Most countries have life expectancy clustered around the median.
  • Outliers on the low end indicate some nations are significantly behind, possibly due to war, famine, epidemics, etc.

Summary:

  • Life expectancy data is slightly skewed, but mostly unimodal and concentrated in a healthy range.
  • A few outliers reflect poor conditions in some countries.

# Using VIF to Quantify Redundancy

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
from statsmodels.tools.tools import add_constant

X = df_imputed.drop(columns=['life_expectancy'])  # drop target
X_const = add_constant(X.select_dtypes(include='number'))  # numeric only

vif_df = pd.DataFrame()
vif_df['feature'] = X_const.columns
vif_df['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_const.values, i) for i in range(X_const.shape[1])]

Interpretation of Correlation Heatmap and VIF Analysis

Correlation Heatmap Analysis

  • Strong Positive Correlations:
    • life_expectancy with income_composition_of_resources (0.74) and schooling (0.77)
    • infant_deaths with under-five_deaths (1.00): this is a perfect correlation indicating these are essentially measuring the same thing
    • thinness_1-19_years with thinness_5-9_years (0.94): very highly correlated
    • income_composition_of_resources with schooling (0.81)
  • Strong Negative Correlations:
    • life_expectancy with adult_mortality (-0.70): as expected, higher mortality lowers life expectancy
    • thinness_1-19_years with income_composition_of_resources (-0.43) and schooling (-0.48)
  • Interesting Relationships:
    • year has very low correlations with other variables (all < 0.24)
    • gdp is highly correlated with percentage_expenditure (0.90)
    • polio and diphtheria are highly correlated (0.67)

VIF Analysis

The Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) confirms multicollinearity issues:

  • Severe Multicollinearity (VIF > 10):
    • Infant Deaths (178.80) & Under-Five Deaths (178.00): Must remove one to avoid model instability.
  • High Multicollinearity (5 VIF < 10):
    • Thinness 1-19 Years (8.77) & Thinness 5-9 Years (8.85): Nearly identical > keep only one.
    • GDP (6.21) & Percentage Expenditure (5.91): Economic indicators with strong overlap.
  • Moderate Multicollinearity (VIF < 5):
    • Schooling (4.01) & Income Composition (3.30): Some correlation but may be acceptable if theoretically justified.

Decisions for Model Improvement

  • Remove Redundant Features:
    • Drop under_five_deaths.
    • Drop thinness_5-9_years.
  • Drop year.
  • Retain Key Predictive Features:
    • Income Composition, Schooling, and Adult Mortality are critical due to their strong correlations with life expectancy.

# Visualizing the numerical variables distributions

# Layout config
plots_per_row = 4
num_plots = len(numeric_cols)
num_rows = math.ceil(num_plots / plots_per_row)

# Set up subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, plots_per_row, figsize=(plots_per_row * 4, num_rows * 3))
axes = axes.flatten()

# Plot KDEs
for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols):
    sns.kdeplot(data=df_imputed, x=col, ax=axes[i], fill=True, color='cornflowerblue')
    axes[i].set_title(col, fontsize=10)
    axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', labelrotation=45)

# Hide unused subplots
for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
    axes[j].axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation: What the KDE Plots Show

  • Skewed Distributions (Highly Asymmetric): Variables with strong right or left skew: percentage_expenditure, gdp, measles, population, hiv/aids, under-five_deaths, these have long tails, many values near 0, and few very large values.

These need scaling or transformation.

  • Bimodal or Multimodal Distributions: bmi, income_composition_of_resources, these show multiple peaks could indicate different subpopulations (e.g., developing vs developed countries).

we might want to analyze these separately by status.

  • Relatively Normal Distributions: schooling, total_expenditure, alcohol, more or less bell-shaped

These are in better shape for most models.

Problem: Different Scales Across Variables

We might apply scaling later

In[15]:
# Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE)

from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

lr = LinearRegression()
rfe = RFE(lr, n_features_to_select=10)
rfe.fit(X, y)

selected_features = X.columns[rfe.support_]
print("Selected features:", list(selected_features))

Selected features: ['status', 'alcohol', 'bmi', 'polio', 'total_expenditure', 'diphtheria', 'hiv/aids', 'thinness_1-19_years', 'income_composition_of_resources', 'schooling']
  • RandomForestRegressor (Tree-based Model):
    • Feature importances:
      • income_composition_of_resources: ~0.50
      • hiv/aids: ~0.33
      • adult_mortality: ~0.10
      • All others: < 0.03
    • This tells us that these top 3 features are doing almost all the work in explaining life_expectancy using non-linear splits. The rest have minimal or no contribution in this model.
  • LinearRegression + RFE:
    • Selected 10 features: these are features that are linearly predictive, not necessarily the most powerful for complex models.
    • LinearRegression is sensitive to multicollinearity and scale, so features like schooling and total_expenditure may seem more valuable here than they really are in a non-linear context.

Features to choose: Top features of RandomForestClassifier model that also appear in the result of the LinearRegression model.

# Creating empty lists
model_names = []
r2_scores = []
rmse_scores = []

# Appending model results
model_names.append("Linear Regression")
r2_scores.append(r2_score(y_test, y_pred_lr))
rmse_scores.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_lr))  # correct usage

model_names.append("Random Forest")
r2_scores.append(r2_score(y_test, y_pred_rf))
rmse_scores.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_rf))

model_names.append("Ridge")
r2_scores.append(r2_score(y_test, y_pred_ridge))
rmse_scores.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_ridge))

model_names.append("XGBoost")
r2_scores.append(r2_score(y_test, y_pred_xgb))
rmse_scores.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_xgb))

# Creating results DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "Model": model_names,
    "R2": r2_scores,
    "RMSE": rmse_scores
})

# Sort and display
results_df.sort_values(by="R2", ascending=False)

Interpretation

  • Random Forest is the clear winner, it captures non-linear relationships exceptionally well.
  • XGBoost is very close and may generalize slightly better in some scenarios.
  • Ridge and Linear Regression performed poorly, they can't capture complex relationships in the data, and the regularization in Ridge didnt help in this case.

What This Tells Us

  • The target variable (life_expectancy) depends on non-linear interactions.
  • Linear models arent appropriate here.

Final Model Choice: RandomForest model

In[25]:
# Cross-Validation

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
import numpy as np

rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=0)

# 5-Fold CV using R score
scores = cross_val_score(rf, X, y, cv=5, scoring='r2')

print("Cross-Validation R Scores:", scores)
print("Mean R:", np.mean(scores))
print("Standard Deviation:", np.std(scores))

Cross-Validation R Scores: [0.93086225 0.90025458 0.91653784 0.91387086 0.92887802]
Mean R: 0.918080710283348
Standard Deviation: 0.011115969661346382

Interpretation

  • The Random Forest model is performing very well across different subsets of the data.
  • There's no major data leakage, no overfitting, and strong generalizability.
  • This strengthens our case for choosing Random Forest as the final model.

Interpretation

  • The Random Forest model is doing very well.
  • It doesnt systematically over- or under-predict at any specific range.
  • No strong heteroscedasticity or bias: residuals are fairly evenly distributed.

We can be confident that:

  • The model is not overfitting.
  • There's no major issue in model assumptions.
  • The model generalizes well, which was also confirmed by cross-validation.
